    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-07-04T04:25:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-07-04T04:25:00-05:00" n="595"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d595">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/432: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ethiopia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">George</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Addis Ababa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-04T12:00:00+02:35"
                            >July 4, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received July 4—6:42 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>52. Unexpectedly summoned to Palace last evening. Emperor gave me oral résumé of
                    events past 6 months concluding that since <pb facs="0826" n="724"
                        xml:id="pg_724"/> Eden visit to Rome<note n="35" xml:id="d595fn35">June
                        24–26. See statement by Anthony Eden in the House of Commons, Hansard, July
                        1, 1935, col. 1520–1522.</note> Italy’s intention conquest beyond doubt.
                    Referring to last December’s exchange with Department (see my telegram of Dec.
                    19, 10 a.m.<note n="36" xml:id="d595fn36">
                        <ref target="frus1934v02#pg_770">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1934, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 770</ref>.</note>), Emperor declared he
                    will continue to pursue Geneva procedure but feels it his duty to ask American
                    Government “to examine means of securing Italy’s observance of engagements as
                    signatory of the Kellogg Pact”. I had previously mentioned and now repeated
                    circumstances of 1931 invocation.<note n="37" xml:id="d595fn37">See telegram No.
                        22, December 18, 1934, 5 p.m., to the Chargé in Ethiopia, <ref
                            target="frus1934v02#pg_769">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 769</ref>.</note> Emperor’s oral
                    statement immediately confirmed in writing and being released to press.<note
                        n="38" xml:id="d595fn38">Text of Ethiopian note not found in Department
                        files; for content of the note, see London <hi rend="italic">Times</hi>,
                        July 6, 1935, p. 12.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">George</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
